a/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=837&lang=e&dCode=&StationName=RICHMOND&SearchType=Contains&province=ALL&provBut=Go&month1=0&month2=12\n| title = Richmond Nature Park British Columbia\n| work = Canadian Climate Normals 1981\u20132010\n| accessdate = 20 March 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Contemporary home in Richmond, BC.JPG|thumb|right|Old Richmond home, 2006]]\nRichmond's 2016 population of 198,309 makes it the fourth largest city in British Columbia, after [[Vancouver]] (631,486), [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]] (517,887) and [[Burnaby]] (232,755).\n\nRichmond has an [[immigrant]] population of 60%, the highest in Canada.<ref name=60%immig>{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/richmondnews/news/story.html?id=add39b4e-452d-454b-b7a8-f35890156593&k=7115|title=Richmond has highest percentage of immigrants in Canada}}</ref> Over 50% of Richmond residents identify as Chinese, making it the city in North America with the largest proportion of Asians.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bhatty |first=Ayesha |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-radio-and-tv-18149316 |title=Canada prepares for an Asian future |publisher=BBC|date=25 May 2012|accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> More than half of its population is of Asian descent, many of whom immigrated in the late 1980s, mostly from [[Hong Kong]], [[Republic of China|Taiwan]], and [[China|Mainland China]]. Other [[Asian Canadian]]s in Richmond include [[Indo-Canadians]], [[Filipino Canadian]]s and [[Japanese Canadians]].<ref name=\"statscan\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5915015&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=&SearchText=&SearchType=&SearchPR=&B1=Population |title=Richmond at Statistics Canada |publisher=2.statcan.ca |date=12 March 2002 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref>\n\nRichmond's Japanese community has a long history in [[Steveston, British Columbia|Steveston]] dating back to the 1800s. Following Japan's 1941 [[Pearl Harbor attack|attack on Pearl Harbor]], the [[Anti-Japanese sentiment]] grew and this community was devastated as residents of Japanese descent were relocated to [[Japanese Canadian internment|internment camps]]  in the [[Interior Plateau|BC Interior]] and [[Alberta]] and their property sold at auction.\n\nRichmond is also home to two of the largest Buddhist temples in North America, the [[International Buddhist Temple]] and the [[Ling Yen Mountain Temple]].\n\nThe average price of a detached home in Richmond is CAN$1,581,600.<ref>{{cite web |title=How Much Did Vancouver Home Prices Fall in January? {{!}} Zoocasa |url=https://www.zoocasa.com/blog/vancouver-home-prices-january-2019/ |website=Zoocasa Blog |accessdate=14 October 2019 |date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Historical populations\n| title = Historical populations\n| type  = Canada\n| align       = right\n| width       =\n| state       =\n| shading     =\n| percentages =\n| footnote    = <ref>[http://www.citypopulation.de/Canada-BritishColumbia.html citypopulation.de], British Columbia (Canada): Province, Major Cities, Towns & District Municipalities \u2013 Statistics</ref>\n|1981|96154\n|1991|126624\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|148867\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|164345\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|174461\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|190473\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|198309 \n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Canada 2016 Census!! Population !! % of Total Population\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" | [[Visible minority]] group<br /><small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5933042&Data=Count&SearchText=Richmond&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5915025&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Richmond&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Visible%20minority&Custom= |title=Community Profiles from the 2011 Census, Statistics Canada \u2013 Census Subdivision |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=6 December 2010 |ac