itical terminology]]\n[[Category:Populism]]\n", "name_user": "Red dwarf", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right-wing_populism"}
{"title_page": "Aziz Sahmaoui", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Aziz Sahmaoui <br/>\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0648\u064a\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Aziz Sahmaoui & University of Gnawa - Festival du bout du monde 2012 - 019.jpg\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Aziz Sahmaoui in [[2012]].\n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = [[1962]]\n| birth_place      = [[Marrakesh]]\n| origin           = [[Morocco]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date first) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Gnawa music|Gnawa]]<br/>[[World music]]\n| occupation       = [[Musician]]<br/>[[Singer]]<br/>Percussionist\n| instrument       = [[Sintir]]<br/>[[Oud]]<br/>[[Guitar]]\n| years_active     = [[1995]] \u2013 present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.azizsahmaoui.com/}}\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n'''Aziz Sahmaoui''' (in [[Arabic]]: \u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0648\u064a) (born 1962 in [[Marrakesh]]) is a Moroccan musician (vocalist - percussionist) specialized in the modern [[Gnawa music]].\n\n==Early life==\nAziz Sahmaoui was born in [[1962]] in [[Marrakesh]] and grew up in the red city. He started listening to [[Gnawa music]] since his young age, influenced by his father. After finishing his studies, he moved by the 1990's to [[Paris]] where he co-founded the National Orchestra of Barb\u00e8s (in [[French language|French]]: ''l'Orchestre National de Barb\u00e8s'' - ONB)<ref>[https://www.afro.video/en/artist/aziz-sahmaoui/ Aziz Sahmaoui - Afro Video]</ref>, which mixed [[Reggae]] and [[Ra\u00ef]] with North African incluences<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/oct/06/aziz-sahmaoui-university-of-gnawa-review Aziz Sahmaoui and University of Gnawa \u2013 review - The Guardian (2011).]</ref>.\n\nAfter releasing two albums with ONB, he joined the pianist [[Joe Zawinul]] and collaborated with him in a number of songs<ref>[https://www.azizsahmaoui.com/ Biography of Aziz Sahmaoui]</ref>. In [[2010]], Sahmaoui founded his own band, The University of Gnawa, having members from various countries including [[France]], [[Senegal]] and North Africa. Inspired by its founder's experience, the band shows traces of many genres: North African Paris, ethno-Jazz Fusion, [[Ra\u00ef]], [[Chaabi]] and [[Music of West Africa|traditional West African music]]. Its core curriculum remains though: The deep exploration of Gnawa trance music<ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/8331ccfc-ed5c-11e0-be97-00144feab49a University of Gnawa: University of Gnawa ft. Aziz Sahmaoui - Financial Times (2011).]</ref>.\n\nIn [[2014]], Aziz Sahmaoui applied for the Algerian citizenship, saying that: \u201cI\u2019d love to be an Algerian Citizen. It would be such an honor for me. Maybe this is a right, but it will be a joy, a privilege, an honor to be an Algerian citizen.\u201d<ref>[https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2014/08/136837/moroccan-singer-seeks-to-obtain-algerian-citizenship-2/ Moroccan Singer Seeks to Obtain Algerian Citizenship - Morocco World News (2014).]</ref>.\n==Discography==\nDuring his career, Aziz Sahmaoui recorded several albums, including:\n* ''Poetic Trance'' (2019) - With University of Gnawa\n* ''Mazal'' (2014) - With University of Gnawa\n* ''University of Gnawa'' (2011)  - With University of Gnawa\n* ''75'' (2008)  - With [[Joe Zawinul]]\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:People from Marrakesh]]\n[[Category:Moroccan singers]]\n[[Category:North African music]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Aziz Sahmaoui <br/>\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0648\u064a\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Aziz Sahmaoui & University of Gnawa - Festival du bout du monde 2012 - 019.jpg\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Aziz Sahmaoui in [[2012]].\n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = [[1962]]\n| birth_place      = [[Marrakesh]]\n| origin           = [[Morocco]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date first) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Gnawa music|Gnawa]]<br/>[[World music]]\n| occupation       = [[Musician]]<br/>[[Singer]]<br/>Percussionist\n| instrument       = [[Sintir]]<br/>[[Oud]]<br/>[[Guitar]]\n| years_active     = [[1995]] \u2013 present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.azizsahmaoui.com/}}\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n'''Aziz Sahmaoui''' (in [[Arabic]]: \u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0648\u064a) (born 1962 in [[Marrakesh]]) is a Moroccan musician (vocalist - percussionist) specialized in the modern [[Gnawa music]].\n\n==Early life==\nAziz Sahmaoui was born in [[1962]] in [[Marrakesh]] and grew up in the red city. He started listening to [[Gnawa music]] since his young age, influenced by his father. After finishing his studies, he moved by the 1990's to [[Paris]] where he co-founded the National Orchestra of Barb\u00e8s (in [[French]]: ''l'Orchestre National de Barb\u00e8s'' - ONB)<ref>[https://www.afro.video/en/artist/aziz-sahmaoui/ Aziz Sahmaoui - Afro Video]</ref>, which mixed [[Reggae]] and [[Ra\u00ef]] with North African incluences<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/oct/06/aziz-sahmaoui-university-of-gnawa-review Aziz Sahmaoui and University of Gnawa \u2013 review - The Guardian (2011).]</ref>.\n\nAfter releasing two albums with ONB, he joined the pianist [[Joe Zawinul]] and collaborated with him in a number of songs<ref>[https://www.azizsahmaoui.com/ Biography of Aziz Sahmaoui]</ref>. In [[2010]], Sahmaoui founded his own band, The University of Gnawa, having members from various countries including [[France]], [[Senegal]] and North Africa. Inspired by its founder's experience, the band shows traces of many genres: North African Paris, ethno-Jazz Fusion, [[Ra\u00ef]], [[Chaabi]] and [[Music of West Africa|traditional West African music]]. Its core curriculum remains though: The deep exploration of Gnawa trance music<ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/8331ccfc-ed5c-11e0-be97-00144feab49a University of Gnawa: University of Gnawa ft. Aziz Sahmaoui - Financial Times (2011).]</ref>.\n\nIn [[2014]], Aziz Sahmaoui applied for the Algerian citizenship, saying that: \u201cI\u2019d love to be an Algerian Citizen. It would be such an honor for me. Maybe this is a right, but it will be a joy, a privilege, an honor to be an Algerian citizen.\u201d<ref>[https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2014/08/136837/moroccan-singer-seeks-to-obtain-algerian-citizenship-2/ Moroccan Singer Seeks to Obtain Algerian Citizenship - Morocco World News (2014).]</ref>.\n==Discography==\nDuring his career, Aziz Sahmaoui recorded several albums, including:\n* ''Poetic Trance'' (2019) - With University of Gnawa\n* ''Mazal'' (2014) - With University of Gnawa\n* ''University of Gnawa'' (2011)  - With University of Gnawa\n* ''75'' (2008)  - With [[Joe Zawinul]]\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:People from Marrakesh]]\n[[Category:Moroccan singers]]\n[[Category:North African music]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toFrench(link changed toFrench language) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aziz_Sahmaoui"}
{"title_page": "Easter Bilby", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian holiday character}}\n[[File:Haighs Easter Bilby Nicole Kearney.jpg|thumb|A bilby made of chocolate with other bilbies printed on a mug.]]\nThe '''Easter Bilby''' gets a knoife, and mehdahs children.\n\n== Origin ==\n [[File:Macrotis lagotis Gould.jpg|thumb|right|A [[bilby]] as illustrated by [[John Gould]]]]\n\n[[Bilby|Bilbies]] are native Australian [[marsupial]]s that are endangered. To raise money and increase awareness of conservation efforts, bilby-shaped chocolates and related merchandise are sold within many stores throughout Australia as an alternative to [[Easter]] bunnies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deh.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/tsd05greater-bilby.html |title=Greater Bilby |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=2007-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070125103406/http://www.deh.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/tsd05greater-bilby.html |archive-date=2007-01-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe first documented use of the Easter Bilby concept was in March 1968 when a 9-year-old girl Rose-Marie Dusting, wrote a story, \"Billy The Aussie Easter Bilby,\" which she published as a book 11 years later.  The story helped catalyse the public's interest in saving the bilby.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2012/04/04/150005331/chocolate-bilbies-not-bunnies-for-an-australian-easter|title=Chocolate Bilbies, Not Bunnies, For An Australian Easter|website=NPR.org}}</ref>\nIn 1991, Nicholas Newland from the 'Foundation for Rabbit-Free Australia' also developed the idea of the Easter Bilby to raise awareness about the environmental damage that [[feral]] [[rabbits]] cause and to replace the Easter bunny with true native wildlife.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitfreeaustralia.org.au/|title=Foundation for Rabbit-Free Australia|access-date=2008-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080803010404/http://www.rabbitfreeaustralia.org.au/|archive-date=2008-08-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first Chocolate Easter Bilbies were sold at the [[Warrawong Sanctuary]] when it was owned by [[John Wamsley]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TAjxHMyA1cgC&pg=PP159&dq=wamsley+easter+bilby/|title=Facing the Wild: Ecotourism, Conservation and Animal Encounters|isbn=9781136548109|last1=Bulbeck|first1=Chilla|date=2012-06-25}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nChocolate manufacturers that donate towards bilby conservation include [[Pink Lady (chocolate wholesaler)|Pink Lady]] and [[Haigh's Chocolates]]. In 2014, Pink Lady donated 30 cents from every large bilby sale and $1 from every 10 pack. Parent company Fyna Foods manufactures chocolate bilbies as well as other iconic Australian fauna in their Australian Bush Friends Easter chocolate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://savethebilbyfund.com/application/files/8414/8227/9182/2016_Bilby_Update_eNewsletter.pdf|title=Bilby Update: 2016 in review|accessdate=29 March 2018}}</ref> 20 cents from every Bush Friends collection is donated to the Save the Bilby Fund. 2015 saw these chocolates raise over $33,000 to the fund.\n\nFor three years prior to 2018, Cadbury donated $10,000 per year to the Save the Bilby Fund, although they were not an official partner.  {{as of|2018}}, the Cadbury bilbies were discontinued, resulting in major supermarkets Coles and Woolworths not stocking any chocolate bilbies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/news/2018/03/easter-bilby-chocolate-cadbury-discontinued|title=This is why you're having trouble finding chocolate bilbies this Easter|work=Australian Geographic|accessdate=29 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDarrell Lea began selling chocolate bilbies in 1999.<ref name=\":0\"/>  As of 2009, sales of Darrell Lea's bilbies were about the same as their sales of bunnies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/bilby-fatigue-as-rabbits-win-the-easter-chocolate-war-20090409-a287.html|title=Bilby fatigue as rabbits win the Easter chocolate war|last1=Murray|first1=Elicia|date=9 April 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=29 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>  From 1999 to 2008, Darrell Lea raised $300,000 towards the Save the Bilby Fund.<ref name=\":0\"/>  Prior to their store closures in 2012, Darrell Lea donated approximately $60,000 per year to the Save the Bilby Fund from the sales of the Darrell Lea chocolate bilbies.\n\nAustralian children's book author and illustrator [[Irena Sibley]] produced three Easter Bilby books between 1994 and 2000 including the best selling ''The Bilbies' First Easter'',  published by Silver Gum Press in 1994.\n\nIn 1993, Australian children's author Jeni Bright wrote the story of \"Burra Nimu, the Easter Bilby\".  It tells how Burra, a shy but brave little bilby, decides to save the land from the rabbits and foxes who are ruining it.  Burra and his family and friends gather together for a wonderful time painting Easter eggs to give to the children and ask for their help.  But before they can set off on their journey to the children, they must outwit the rabbit army. As well as the story of the Easter Bilby, the not-for-profit website [http://www.easterbilby.info/ 'Burra Nimu, the Easter Bilby'] contains factual information about bilbies and other endangered Australian species.  It is illustrated by Australian illustrator Janet Selby.\n\nIn 2003, funds from the sale of chocolate bilbies were used to build a 20&nbsp;km-long predator-proof fence in [[Currawinya National Park]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Wild about bilbies and a rabbit-proof Easter - smh.com.au|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/04/18/1050172755503.html|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=www.smh.com.au}}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2017}}, consumers were urged to buy chocolate bilbies with a green tag, signifying that the sale raises funds for the bilby.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/queenslanders-urged-to-buy-easter-bilbies-but-beware-of-the-fakes-20170415-gvliv9.html|title=Queenslanders urged to buy Easter bilbies but beware of the fakes|last1=Caldwell|first1=Felicity|date=15 April 2017|work=Brisbane Times|language=en}}</ref> Nevertheless, research has shown that throughout the last decade the concept of the Easter bilby has seen decrease interest in Australia, as shown by online searches and mentions in major newspapers.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ver\u00edssimo|first=Diogo|date=December 2017|title=The Easter Bilby as a counter-marketing strategy for biodiversity conservation|url=http://www.scielo.mec.pt/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&pid=S1645-44642017000300006&lng=en&nrm=iso&tlng=en|journal=Revista de Gest\u00e3o Dos Pa\u00edses de L\u00edngua Portuguesa|volume=16|issue=3|pages=59\u201372|issn=1645-4464}}</ref> This, coupled with changes in the Australian chocolate industry, including the decision of Cadbury and Darrell Lea to stop making chocolate bilbies, have meant that the Easter bilby is increasingly a niche product, removed from mainstream Australian culture.<ref name=\":0\" />\nIn 2019, Cadbury announced it will no longer make the chocolate bilbies, and no major supermarkets carried them.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Where are all the chocolate bilbies this year? |journal=Australian Geographic |date=15 April 2019 |url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/history-culture/2019/04/where-are-all-the-chocolate-bilbies-this-year/ |language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Rabbits in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Easter}}\n\n[[Category:Easter traditions]]\n[[Category:Holiday characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional marsupials]]\n[[Category:Australian folklore]]\n[[Category:Peramelemorphs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian holiday character}}\n[[File:Haighs Easter Bilby Nicole Kearney.jpg|thumb|A bilby made of chocolate with other bilbies printed on a mug.]]\nThe '''Easter Bilby''' is an [[Australia]]n alternative to the [[Easter Bunny]].\n\n== Origin ==\n [[File:Macrotis lagotis Gould.jpg|thumb|right|A [[bilby]] as illustrated by [[John Gould]]]]\n\n[[Bilby|Bilbies]] are native Australian [[marsupial]]s that are endangered. To raise money and increase awareness of conservation efforts, bilby-shaped chocolates and related merchandise are sold within many stores throughout Australia as an alternative to [[Easter]] bunnies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deh.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/tsd05greater-bilby.html |title=Greater Bilby |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=2007-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070125103406/http://www.deh.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/tsd05greater-bilby.html |archive-date=2007-01-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe first documented use of the Easter Bilby concept was in March 1968 when a 9-year-old girl Rose-Marie Dusting, wrote a story, \"Billy The Aussie Easter Bilby,\" which she published as a book 11 years later.  The story helped catalyse the public's interest in saving the bilby.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2012/04/04/150005331/chocolate-bilbies-not-bunnies-for-an-australian-easter|title=Chocolate Bilbies, Not Bunnies, For An Australian Easter|website=NPR.org}}</ref>\nIn 1991, Nicholas Newland from the 'Foundation for Rabbit-Free Australia' also developed the idea of the Easter Bilby to raise awareness about the environmental damage that [[feral]] [[rabbits]] cause and to replace the Easter bunny with true native wildlife.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitfreeaustralia.org.au/|title=Foundation for Rabbit-Free Australia|access-date=2008-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080803010404/http://www.rabbitfreeaustralia.org.au/|archive-date=2008-08-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first Chocolate Easter Bilbies were sold at the [[Warrawong Sanctuary]] when it was owned by [[John Wamsley]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TAjxHMyA1cgC&pg=PP159&dq=wamsley+easter+bilby/|title=Facing the Wild: Ecotourism, Conservation and Animal Encounters|isbn=9781136548109|last1=Bulbeck|first1=Chilla|date=2012-06-25}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nChocolate manufacturers that donate towards bilby conservation include [[Pink Lady (chocolate wholesaler)|Pink Lady]] and [[Haigh's Chocolates]]. In 2014, Pink Lady donated 30 cents from every large bilby sale and $1 from every 10 pack. Parent company Fyna Foods manufactures chocolate bilbies as well as other iconic Australian fauna in their Australian Bush Friends Easter chocolate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://savethebilbyfund.com/application/files/8414/8227/9182/2016_Bilby_Update_eNewsletter.pdf|title=Bilby Update: 2016 in review|accessdate=29 March 2018}}</ref> 20 cents from every Bush Friends collection is donated to the Save the Bilby Fund. 2015 saw these chocolates raise over $33,000 to the fund.\n\nFor three years prior to 2018, Cadbury donated $10,000 per year to the Save the Bilby Fund, although they were not an official partner.  {{as of|2018}}, the Cadbury bilbies were discontinued, resulting in major supermarkets Coles and Woolworths not stocking any chocolate bilbies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/news/2018/03/easter-bilby-chocolate-cadbury-discontinued|title=This is why you're having trouble finding chocolate bilbies this Easter|work=Australian Geographic|accessdate=29 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDarrell Lea began selling chocolate bilbies in 1999.<ref name=\":0\"/>  As of 2009, sales of Darrell Lea's bilbies were about the same as their sales of bunnies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/bilby-fatigue-as-rabbits-win-the-easter-chocolate-war-20090409-a287.html|title=Bilby fatigue as rabbits win the Easter chocolate war|last1=Murray|first1=Elicia|date=9 April 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=29 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>  From 1999 to 2008, Darrell Lea raised $300,000 towards the Save the Bilby Fund.<ref name=\":0\"/>  Prior to their store closures in 2012, Darrell Lea donated approximately $60,000 per year to the Save the Bilby Fund from the sales of the Darrell Lea chocolate bilbies.\n\nAustralian children's book author and illustrator [[Irena Sibley]] produced three Easter Bilby books between 1994 and 2000 including the best selling ''The Bilbies' First Easter'',  published by Silver Gum Press in 1994.\n\nIn 1993, Australian children's author Jeni Bright wrote the story of \"Burra Nimu, the Easter Bilby\".  It tells how Burra, a shy but brave little bilby, decides to save the land from the rabbits and foxes who are ruining it.  Burra and his family and friends gather together for a wonderful time painting Easter eggs to give to the children and ask for their help.  But before they can set off on their journey to the children, they must outwit the rabbit army. As well as the story of the Easter Bilby, the not-for-profit website [http://www.easterbilby.info/ 'Burra Nimu, the Easter Bilby'] contains factual information about bilbies and other endangered Australian species.  It is illustrated by Australian illustrator Janet Selby.\n\nIn 2003, funds from the sale of chocolate bilbies were used to build a 20&nbsp;km-long predator-proof fence in [[Currawinya National Park]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Wild about bilbies and a rabbit-proof Easter - smh.com.au|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/04/18/1050172755503.html|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=www.smh.com.au}}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2017}}, consumers were urged to buy chocolate bilbies with a green tag, signifying that the sale raises funds for the bilby.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/queenslanders-urged-to-buy-easter-bilbies-but-beware-of-the-fakes-20170415-gvliv9.html|title=Queenslanders urged to buy Easter bilbies but beware of the fakes|last1=Caldwell|first1=Felicity|date=15 April 2017|work=Brisbane Times|language=en}}</ref> Nevertheless, research has shown that throughout the last decade the concept of the Easter bilby has seen decrease interest in Australia, as shown by online searches and mentions in major newspapers.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ver\u00edssimo|first=Diogo|date=December 2017|title=The Easter Bilby as a counter-marketing strategy for biodiversity conservation|url=http://www.scielo.mec.pt/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&pid=S1645-44642017000300006&lng=en&nrm=iso&tlng=en|journal=Revista de Gest\u00e3o Dos Pa\u00edses de L\u00edngua Portuguesa|volume=16|issue=3|pages=59\u201372|issn=1645-4464}}</ref> This, coupled with changes in the Australian chocolate industry, including the decision of Cadbury and Darrell Lea to stop making chocolate bilbies, have meant that the Easter bilby is increasingly a niche product, removed from mainstream Australian culture.<ref name=\":0\" />\nIn 2019, Cadbury announced it will no longer make the chocolate bilbies, and no major supermarkets carried them.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Where are all the chocolate bilbies this year? |journal=Australian Geographic |date=15 April 2019 |url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/history-culture/2019/04/where-are-all-the-chocolate-bilbies-this-year/ |language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Rabbits in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Easter}}\n\n[[Category:Easter traditions]]\n[[Category:Holiday characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional marsupials]]\n[[Category:Australian folklore]]\n[[Category:Peramelemorphs]]\n", "name_user": "Wolopkf", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Made more accurate)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Easter_Bilby"}
{"title_page": "Waldemar Capucci", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Waldemar Capucci\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Brazilian\n| sport          = [[Shooting sports|Sports shooting]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1929|6|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Waldemar Capucci''' (born 8 June 1929) is a Brazilian [[Shooting sports|sports shooter]]. He competed at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]], the [[1980 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1984 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ca/waldemar-capucci-1.html |title=Waldemar Capucci Olympic Results |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capucci, Waldemar}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in shooting]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Waldemar Capucci\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Brazilian\n| sport          = [[Shooting sports|Sports shooting]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1929|6|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Waldemar Capucci''' (born 8 June 1929) is a Brazilian [[Shooting sports|sports shooter]]. He competed at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]], the [[1980 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1984 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ca/waldemar-capucci-1.html |title=Waldemar Capucci Olympic Results |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capucci, Waldemar}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in shooting]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waldemar_Capucci"}
{"title_page": "Jacques Delors", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[His Excellency]]\n| name       = Jacques Delors\n| image        = Delors 01.jpg\n| order       = 8th \n| office      = President of the European Commission\n| vicepresident      = [[Frans Andriessen]]\n| term_start      = 7 January 1985\n| term_end      = 24 January 1995\n| predecessor      = [[Gaston Thorn]]\n| successor      = [[Jacques Santer]]\n| office1      = [[Minister of the Economy, Finances and Industry (France)|Minister of Finance]]\n| primeminister1      = [[Pierre Mauroy]]\n| term_start1      = 22 May 1981\n| term_end1      = 17 July 1984\n| predecessor1      = [[Ren\u00e9 Monory]]\n| successor1      = [[Pierre B\u00e9r\u00e9govoy]]\n| office2       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start2      = 1 July 1979\n| term_end2      = 25 May 1981 \n| constituency2      = [[East France (European Parliament constituency)|East France]]\n| birth_name       = Jacques Lucien Jean Delors\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1925|7|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = Paris, France\n| death_date      = \n| death_place      = \n| party      = [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]]\n| spouse      = Marie Lephaille (m. 1941)\n| children      = [[Martine Aubry|Martine]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Paris]]\n| religion       = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature        =\n}}\n\n'''Jacques Lucien Jean Delors''' (born 20 July 1925) is a French politician who served as the 8th [[President of the European Commission]] from 1985 to 1995. He served as [[Minister of the Economy, Finances and Industry (France)|Minister of Finance]] of France from 1981 to 1984. He was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] from 1979 to 1981.<ref name=\"europa1\">{{Citation\n | title = European Commission \u2013 Discover the former Presidents\n | url = http://ec.europa.eu/commission_barroso/president/history/delors/index_en.htm\n | accessdate = 21 September 2009\n}}</ref>  As President Delors was the most visible and influential leader in European affairs. He implemented the policies that closely linked the member nations together and tirelessly promoted the need for unity. He had critics but on the whole was well respected for his imagination and commitment to the cause of European unity.  His two main achievements were creating a [[single market]] that made possible allowed the free movement of persons, capital, goods, and services within the Community. He also headed the committee that proposed the monetary union to create the Euro, a new currency to relace individual national currencies. This was done in the 1992 [[Maastricht Treaty]].<ref> Gino Raymond, ''Historical Dictionary of France'' (2008) pp 199-101, 124-25. </ref>\n\n==French politics==\nBorn in [[Paris]] in a family originating from [[Corr\u00e8ze]], Delors first held in the 1940s through the 1960s a series of posts in French banking and state planning with the [[Banque de France]].<ref name=\"europa1\"/> As a member of the [[French Confederation of Christian Workers]], he participated in its secularization and the foundation of the [[French Democratic Confederation of Labour]]. In 1969, he became social affairs adviser to the [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] Prime Minister [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]], a move which was presented as part of Chaban's outreach to the centre-ground and first attracted media attention to Delors personally.<ref name=\"europa1\"/>\n\nIn 1957, Delors left the [[French Democratic Confederation of Labour|CFDT]] when he became a high government official to avoid conflicts of interests. In 1974 Delors joined the [[Socialist Party (France)|French Socialist Party]], with other left-wing Christians. He was one of the rare members of the party to be openly religious, thus challenging its long-standing secular tradition of [[La\u00efcit\u00e9]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biography.yourdictionary.com/jacques-delors|title=Jacques Delors Facts|website=biography.yourdictionary.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-21}}</ref> He served in the [[European Parliament]] from 1979 to 1981, becoming chairman of its Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs, actively taking part in debates about economic, social and monetary policies.<ref name=\"europa1\"/> Under President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], Delors served as Economics and Finance Minister from 1981 to 1983, and Economics, Finance, and Budget Minister from 1983 to 1984.<ref name=\"europa1\"/> He advocated a pause in the social policies, a clear acceptance of the market economy, and an alignment with European [[social democracy]]. Critically, he held the line on France's membership of the [[European Monetary System]] (EMS), giving priority to monetary stability over left-wing spending priorities. Mitterrand flirted with the idea of naming him Prime Minister, but never made the appointment.{{citation needed|date=October 2010}}\n\n==President of the European Commission==\n{{See also|Delors Commission}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078267-0023, Bonn, Ministerpr\u00e4sidenten mit EU-Kommissar Delors-CROPPED.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Delors in 1988]]\nDelors became the [[President of the European Commission]] in January 1985. During his presidency, he oversaw important budgetary reforms and laid the groundwork for the introduction of a [[single market]] within the [[European Community]]. It came into effect on 1 January 1993 and allowed the free movement of persons, capital, goods, and services within the Community.)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ross|first=George|last2=Jenson|first2=Jane|date=2017|title=Reconsidering Jacques Delors' leadership of the European Union|journal=Journal of European Integration|volume=39|issue=2|pages=113\u2013127|doi=10.1080/07036337.2016.1277718|issn=0703-6337}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Jacques-Delors|title=Jacques Delors {{!}} French politician|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDelors also headed the committee that in early 1989 proposed the monetary union to create a new currency --the Euro--to replace individual national currencies. This was done in the 1992 [[Maastricht Treaty]].<ref>Michael J. Baun, \"The Maastricht Treaty as High Politics: Germany, France, and European Integration.\" ''Political Science Quarterly'' 110.4 (1995): 605-624. [http://homes.ieu.edu.tr/~aburgin/IREU%20438%20Policy%20Making%20in%20the%20EU/Additional%20Readings/Additional%20Reading%20for%20students/Baun_The%20Maastricht%20Treaty%20as%20High%20Politics%20Germany%20France%20and%20European%20Integration.pdf  online]</ref>\n\nIn opposition to the strident [[neoliberalism]] of American  President  Ronald Reagan (1981-1989) which dominated the American political agenda, Delors promoted an alternative interpretation of capitalism that embedded it in the European social structure. He synthesized three themes. From the left came favouring the redistribution of wealth, and the protection of the weakest. Second a neo-mercantilist approach wanted to maximize European industrial output.  A third was reliance on the marketplace. His emphasis on the social nature of Europe is been central to a important exceptionalism narrative that became central to the self identification of the European Union. <ref>Alessandra Bitumi, \"\u2018An uplifting tale of Europe\u2019. Jacques Delors and the contradictory quest for a European social model in the Age of Reagan.\" ''Journal of Transatlantic Studies'' 16.3 (2018): 203-221 [http://www.academia.edu/download/61940641/An_uplifting_tale_of_Europe_Jacques_Delors_and_the_contradictory_quest_for_a_European_social_model_in_the_Age_of_Reagan20200130-80255-t7.pdf online].</ref><ref>Laurent Warlouzet,  \"The European Commission facing crisis: social, neo-mercantilist and market-oriented approaches (1967\u201385)\" ''European Review of History: Revue europ\u00e9enne d'histoire'' 26.4 (2019): 703-722.</ref>\n\n==Post-Presidency==\n\nDelors has a longstanding interest in education. Initiator of a French law in 1971 (la formation professionnelle continue \u2013 FPC) requiring firms to set aside part of their profits for educational opportunities for their employees, he also chaired a [http://www.unesco.org UNESCO Commission on Education for the Twenty-first Century] from 1993 to 1996 whose final report was published as [http://www.unesco.org/delors/treasure.htm ''Learning: the Treasure Within'']. This work continues to have a significant influence on discourse on lifelong learning, forming the conceptual foundation for both the Canadian Composite Learning Index as well as the [[European Lifelong Learning Indicators (ELLI)]] project.\n\nIn 1994, members of the [[Socialist Party (France)|French Socialist Party]] attempted to persuade Delors to run for President of France. Polls showed that he would have a very good chance of defeating either of the main conservative contenders \u2013 Prime Minister [[\u00c9douard Balladur]] and Mayor of Paris [[Jacques Chirac]].<ref name=\"washpost\">{{Citation\n | title = Delors' Vow Not to Run Could Boost French Anti-Europe Forces\n | date = 13 Dec 1994\n | journal=Washington Post\n}}</ref> However Delors declined to run and the eventual Socialist nominee, [[Lionel Jospin]], was defeated in the [[1995 French presidential election|1995 presidential election]] by Jacques Chirac.\n\nIn 1995, Delors won the [[Charles V European Award|Charles V Prize]], awarded by the Fundaci\u00f3n Academia Europea de Yuste\n\nDelors founded the Paris-based, centre-left [[think tank]] [[Notre Europe]] in 1996 and remains one of its presidents. He is president of the ''Conseil de l'emploi, des revenus et de la coh\u00e9sion sociale'', and honorary member of both the ''[[:fr:Institut Aspen France|Institut Aspen France]]'' and the [[Club of Rome]].\n\nOn 15 September 2010 Delors supported the new initiative [[Spinelli Group]], which was founded to reinvigorate the strive for federalisation of the [[European Union]]. Other prominent supporters include [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], [[Guy Verhofstadt]], [[Sylvie Goulard]], [[Andrew Duff]], and [[Elmar Brok]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spinelligroup.eu/who-we-are/|title=Spinelli group website, Members of the steering group|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921204036/http://www.spinelligroup.eu/who-we-are/|archivedate=21 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, Delors was the first to be honored with the [[Leonardo European Corporate Learning Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leonardo-award.eu|title=Leonardo|website=www.leonardo-award.eu|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Delors received the [[Four Freedoms Award#Freedom Medal|Freedom medal]].<ref>[[Four Freedoms Award#Freedom Medal]]</ref>\n\nDelors is the father of Socialist politician [[Martine Aubry]].<ref name=\"europa1\"/>\n\nIn 2012, Delors stated in the ''[[Handelsblatt]]'' newspaper that \"If the British cannot support the trend towards more integration in Europe, we can nevertheless remain friends, but on a different basis. I could imagine a form such as a European economic area or a free-trade agreement.\" \n\nOn 25 June 2015, [[Donald Tusk]] announced that Delors would become the third person ever to have the title of [[Honorary Citizen of Europe]] bestowed upon them, in recognition of \"his remarkable contribution to the development of the European project\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2015/06/24-tusk-invitation-letter-european-council/|title=Invitation letter by President Donald Tusk to the members of the European Council - Consilium|website=www.consilium.europa.eu|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n\nHe is the father of [[Martine Aubry]] (born 1950), who served as the [[First Secretary of the French Socialist Party]] 2008\u20132012.\n\n== Honours ==\n* '''1999''': Member of the [[Royal Academy of Science, Letters and Fine Arts of Belgium]].<ref>Index biographique des membres et associ\u00e9s de l'Acad\u00e9mie royale de Belgique (1769-2005). p83</ref>\n* Grand Cross of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany.\n\n==Selected works==\n{{Citation\n | title = M\u00e9moires\n | year = 2004\n | publisher=Plon\n | isbn = 978-2-259-19292-7\n | last1 = Delors     | first1 = Jacques\n | last2 = Arnaud     | first2 = Jean-Louis    }}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Delors Commission]]\n*[[Economic and Monetary Union of the European Union]]\n*[[Notre Europe]]\n*[[Spinelli Group]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*  Bitumi, Alessandra. \"\u2018An uplifting tale of Europe\u2019. Jacques Delors and the contradictory quest for a European social model in the Age of Reagan.\" ''Journal of Transatlantic Studies'' 16.3 (2018): 203-221. [http://www.academia.edu/download/61940641/An_uplifting_tale_of_Europe_Jacques_Delors_and_the_contradictory_quest_for_a_European_social_model_in_the_Age_of_Reagan20200130-80255-t7.pdf Online]\n* Drake, Helen. ''Jacques Delors: perspectives on a European leader'' (Psychology Press, 2000).\n* Drake, Helen. \"Political leadership and European integration: the case of Jacques Delors.\" ''West European Politics'' 18.1 (1995): 140-160.  [http://aei.pitt.edu/7120/1/002168_1.pdf   Online]\n* Endo, Ken. ''The presidency of the European Commission under Jacques Delors: The politics of shared leadership'' (Springer, 1999).\n* Ross, George, and Jane Jenson. \"Reconsidering Jacques Delors\u2019 leadership of the European union.\" ''Journal of European Integration'' 39.2 (2017): 113-127.\n* Van Assche, Tobias. \"The impact of entrepreneurial leadership on EU high politics: A case study of Jacques Delors and the creation of EMU.\" ''Leadership'' 1.3 (2005): 279-298.\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Jacques Delors}}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/cta/events02/world/eur/euro/delors.ram Delors addressing the British trade unions]\n* The famous headline from ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' in the UK: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/nol/shared/spl/hi/pop_ups/06/programmes_enl_1146754853/img/1.jpg \"Up Yours Delors\"]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ren\u00e9 Monory]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of the Economy, Finances and Industry (France)|Minister of Finance]]|years=1981\u20131984}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pierre B\u00e9r\u00e9govoy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Ortoli]]<br />[[Edgard Pisani]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of European Commissioners by nationality#France|French European Commissioner]]|years=1985\u20131995|alongside=[[Claude Cheysson]], [[Christiane Scrivener]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[\u00c9dith Cresson]]<br />[[Yves-Thibault de Silguy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gaston Thorn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the European Commission]]|years=1985\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jacques Santer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Margaret Thatcher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Speaker at the [[College of Europe]] Opening Ceremony|years=1989}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{European Commission}}\n{{Finance Ministers of France}}\n{{Charlemagne Prize recipients}}\n{{UEFA President's Award}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for International Cooperation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delors, Jacques}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:French Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:French Confederation of Christian Workers members]]\n[[Category:French Democratic Confederation of Labour members]]\n[[Category:French economists]]\n[[Category:French European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:French Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MEPs for France 1979\u20131984]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the European Commission]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Socialist Party (France) politicians]]\n[[Category:Unified Socialist Party (France) politicians]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Finance]]\n[[Category:Catholic socialists]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses 1st class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bavarian Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Academy of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Four Freedoms Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[His Excellency]]\n| name       = Jacques Delors\n| image        = Delors 01.jpg\n| order       = 8th \n| office      = President of the European Commission\n| vicepresident      = [[Frans Andriessen]]\n| term_start      = 7 January 1985\n| term_end      = 24 January 1995\n| predecessor      = [[Gaston Thorn]]\n| successor      = [[Jacques Santer]]\n| office1      = [[Minister of the Economy, Finances and Industry (France)|Minister of Finance]]\n| primeminister1      = [[Pierre Mauroy]]\n| term_start1      = 22 May 1981\n| term_end1      = 17 July 1984\n| predecessor1      = [[Ren\u00e9 Monory]]\n| successor1      = [[Pierre B\u00e9r\u00e9govoy]]\n| office2       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start2      = 1 July 1979\n| term_end2      = 25 May 1981 \n| constituency2      = [[East France (European Parliament constituency)|East France]]\n| birth_name       = Jacques Lucien Jean Delors\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1925|7|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = Paris, France\n| death_date      = \n| death_place      = \n| party      = [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]]\n| spouse      = Marie Lephaille (m. 1941)\n| children      = [[Martine Aubry|Martine]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Paris]]\n| religion       = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature        =\n}}\n\n'''Jacques Lucien Jean Delors''' (born 20 July 1925) is a French politician who served as the 8th [[President of the European Commission]] from 1985 to 1995. He served as [[Minister of the Economy, Finances and Industry (France)|Minister of Finance]] of France from 1981 to 1984. He was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] from 1979 to 1981.<ref name=\"europa1\">{{Citation\n | title = European Commission \u2013 Discover the former Presidents\n | url = http://ec.europa.eu/commission_barroso/president/history/delors/index_en.htm\n | accessdate = 21 September 2009\n}}</ref>  As President Delors was the most visible and influential leader in European affairs. He implemented the policies that closely linked the member nations together and tirelessly promoted the need for unity. He had critics but on the whole was well respected for his imagination and commitment to the cause of European unity.  His two main achievements were creating a [[single market]] that made possible allowed the free movement of persons, capital, goods, and services within the Community. He also headed the committee that proposed the monetary union to create the Euro, a new currency to relace individual national currencies. This was done in the 1992 [[Maastricht Treaty]].<ref> Gino Raymond, ''Historical Dictionary of France'' (2008) pp 199-101, 124-25. </ref>\n\n==French politics==\nBorn in [[Paris]] in a family originating from [[Corr\u00e8ze]], Delors first held in the 1940s through the 1960s a series of posts in French banking and state planning with the [[Banque de France]].<ref name=\"europa1\"/> As a member of the [[French Confederation of Christian Workers]], he participated in its secularization and the foundation of the [[French Democratic Confederation of Labour]]. In 1969, he became social affairs adviser to the [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] Prime Minister [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]], a move which was presented as part of Chaban's outreach to the centre-ground and first attracted media attention to Delors personally.<ref name=\"europa1\"/>\n\nIn 1957, Delors left the [[French Democratic Confederation of Labour|CFDT]] when he became a high government official to avoid conflicts of interests. In 1974 Delors joined the [[Socialist Party (France)|French Socialist Party]], with other left-wing Christians. He was one of the rare members of the party to be openly religious, thus challenging its long-standing secular tradition of [[La\u00efcit\u00e9]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biography.yourdictionary.com/jacques-delors|title=Jacques Delors Facts|website=biography.yourdictionary.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-21}}</ref> He served in the [[European Parliament]] from 1979 to 1981, becoming chairman of its Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs.<ref name=\"europa1\"/> Under President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], Delors served as Economics and Finance Minister from 1981 to 1983, and Economics, Finance, and Budget Minister from 1983 to 1984.<ref name=\"europa1\"/> He advocated a pause in the social policies, a clear acceptance of the market economy, and an alignment with European [[social democracy]]. Critically, he held the line on France's membership of the [[European Monetary System]] (EMS), giving priority to monetary stability over left-wing spending priorities. Mitterrand flirted with the idea of naming him Prime Minister, but never made the appointment.{{citation needed|date=October 2010}}\n\n==President of the European Commission==\n{{See also|Delors Commission}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078267-0023, Bonn, Ministerpr\u00e4sidenten mit EU-Kommissar Delors-CROPPED.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Delors in 1988]]\nDelors became the [[President of the European Commission]] in January 1985. During his presidency, he oversaw important budgetary reforms and laid the groundwork for the introduction of a [[single market]] within the [[European Community]]. It came into effect on 1 January 1993 and allowed the free movement of persons, capital, goods, and services within the Community.)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ross|first=George|last2=Jenson|first2=Jane|date=2017|title=Reconsidering Jacques Delors' leadership of the European Union|journal=Journal of European Integration|volume=39|issue=2|pages=113\u2013127|doi=10.1080/07036337.2016.1277718|issn=0703-6337}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Jacques-Delors|title=Jacques Delors {{!}} French politician|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDelors also headed the committee that in early 1989 proposed the monetary union to create a new currency --the Euro--to replace individual national currencies. This was done in the 1992 [[Maastricht Treaty]].<ref>Michael J. Baun, \"The Maastricht Treaty as High Politics: Germany, France, and European Integration.\" ''Political Science Quarterly'' 110.4 (1995): 605-624. [http://homes.ieu.edu.tr/~aburgin/IREU%20438%20Policy%20Making%20in%20the%20EU/Additional%20Readings/Additional%20Reading%20for%20students/Baun_The%20Maastricht%20Treaty%20as%20High%20Politics%20Germany%20France%20and%20European%20Integration.pdf  online]</ref>\n\nIn opposition to the strident [[neoliberalism]] of American  President  Ronald Reagan (1981-1989) which dominated the American political agenda, Delors promoted an alternative interpretation of capitalism that embedded it in the European social structure. He synthesized three themes. From the left came favouring the redistribution of wealth, and the protection of the weakest. Second a neo-mercantilist approach wanted to maximize European industrial output.  A third was reliance on the marketplace. His emphasis on the social nature of Europe is been central to a important exceptionalism narrative that became central to the self identification of the European Union. <ref>Alessandra Bitumi, \"\u2018An uplifting tale of Europe\u2019. Jacques Delors and the contradictory quest for a European social model in the Age of Reagan.\" ''Journal of Transatlantic Studies'' 16.3 (2018): 203-221 [http://www.academia.edu/download/61940641/An_uplifting_tale_of_Europe_Jacques_Delors_and_the_contradictory_quest_for_a_European_social_model_in_the_Age_of_Reagan20200130-80255-t7.pdf online].</ref><ref>Laurent Warlouzet,  \"The European Commission facing crisis: social, neo-mercantilist and market-oriented approaches (1967\u201385)\" ''European Review of History: Revue europ\u00e9enne d'histoire'' 26.4 (2019): 703-722.</ref>\n\n==Post-Presidency==\n\nDelors has a longstanding interest in education. Initiator of a French law in 1971 (la formation professionnelle continue \u2013 FPC) requiring firms to set aside part of their profits for educational opportunities for their employees, he also chaired a [http://www.unesco.org UNESCO Commission on Education for the Twenty-first Century] from 1993 to 1996 whose final report was published as [http://www.unesco.org/delors/treasure.htm ''Learning: the Treasure Within'']. This work continues to have a significant influence on discourse on lifelong learning, forming the conceptual foundation for both the Canadian Composite Learning Index as well as the [[European Lifelong Learning Indicators (ELLI)]] project.\n\nIn 1994, members of the [[Socialist Party (France)|French Socialist Party]] attempted to persuade Delors to run for President of France. Polls showed that he would have a very good chance of defeating either of the main conservative contenders \u2013 Prime Minister [[\u00c9douard Balladur]] and Mayor of Paris [[Jacques Chirac]].<ref name=\"washpost\">{{Citation\n | title = Delors' Vow Not to Run Could Boost French Anti-Europe Forces\n | date = 13 Dec 1994\n | journal=Washington Post\n}}</ref> However Delors declined to run and the eventual Socialist nominee, [[Lionel Jospin]], was defeated in the [[1995 French presidential election|1995 presidential election]] by Jacques Chirac.\n\nIn 1995, Delors won the [[Charles V European Award|Charles V Prize]], awarded by the Fundaci\u00f3n Academia Europea de Yuste\n\nDelors founded the Paris-based, centre-left [[think tank]] [[Notre Europe]] in 1996 and remains one of its presidents. He is president of the ''Conseil de l'emploi, des revenus et de la coh\u00e9sion sociale'', and honorary member of both the ''[[:fr:Institut Aspen France|Institut Aspen France]]'' and the [[Club of Rome]].\n\nOn 15 September 2010 Delors supported the new initiative [[Spinelli Group]], which was founded to reinvigorate the strive for federalisation of the [[European Union]]. Other prominent supporters include [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], [[Guy Verhofstadt]], [[Sylvie Goulard]], [[Andrew Duff]], and [[Elmar Brok]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spinelligroup.eu/who-we-are/|title=Spinelli group website, Members of the steering group|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921204036/http://www.spinelligroup.eu/who-we-are/|archivedate=21 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, Delors was the first to be honored with the [[Leonardo European Corporate Learning Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leonardo-award.eu|title=Leonardo|website=www.leonardo-award.eu|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Delors received the [[Four Freedoms Award#Freedom Medal|Freedom medal]].<ref>[[Four Freedoms Award#Freedom Medal]]</ref>\n\nDelors is the father of Socialist politician [[Martine Aubry]].<ref name=\"europa1\"/>\n\nIn 2012, Delors stated in the ''[[Handelsblatt]]'' newspaper that \"If the British cannot support the trend towards more integration in Europe, we can nevertheless remain friends, but on a different basis. I could imagine a form such as a European economic area or a free-trade agreement.\" \n\nOn 25 June 2015, [[Donald Tusk]] announced that Delors would become the third person ever to have the title of [[Honorary Citizen of Europe]] bestowed upon them, in recognition of \"his remarkable contribution to the development of the European project\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2015/06/24-tusk-invitation-letter-european-council/|title=Invitation letter by President Donald Tusk to the members of the European Council - Consilium|website=www.consilium.europa.eu|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n\nHe is the father of [[Martine Aubry]] (born 1950), who served as the [[First Secretary of the French Socialist Party]] 2008\u20132012.\n\n== Honours ==\n* '''1999''': Member of the [[Royal Academy of Science, Letters and Fine Arts of Belgium]].<ref>Index biographique des membres et associ\u00e9s de l'Acad\u00e9mie royale de Belgique (1769-2005). p83</ref>\n* Grand Cross of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany.\n\n==Selected works==\n{{Citation\n | title = M\u00e9moires\n | year = 2004\n | publisher=Plon\n | isbn = 978-2-259-19292-7\n | last1 = Delors     | first1 = Jacques\n | last2 = Arnaud     | first2 = Jean-Louis    }}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Delors Commission]]\n*[[Economic and Monetary Union of the European Union]]\n*[[Notre Europe]]\n*[[Spinelli Group]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*  Bitumi, Alessandra. \"\u2018An uplifting tale of Europe\u2019. Jacques Delors and the contradictory quest for a European social model in the Age of Reagan.\" ''Journal of Transatlantic Studies'' 16.3 (2018): 203-221. [http://www.academia.edu/download/61940641/An_uplifting_tale_of_Europe_Jacques_Delors_and_the_contradictory_quest_for_a_European_social_model_in_the_Age_of_Reagan20200130-80255-t7.pdf Online]\n* Drake, Helen. ''Jacques Delors: perspectives on a European leader'' (Psychology Press, 2000).\n* Drake, Helen. \"Political leadership and European integration: the case of Jacques Delors.\" ''West European Politics'' 18.1 (1995): 140-160.  [http://aei.pitt.edu/7120/1/002168_1.pdf   Online]\n* Endo, Ken. ''The presidency of the European Commission under Jacques Delors: The politics of shared leadership'' (Springer, 1999).\n* Ross, George, and Jane Jenson. \"Reconsidering Jacques Delors\u2019 leadership of the European union.\" ''Journal of European Integration'' 39.2 (2017): 113-127.\n* Van Assche, Tobias. \"The impact of entrepreneurial leadership on EU high politics: A case study of Jacques Delors and the creation of EMU.\" ''Leadership'' 1.3 (2005): 279-298.\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Jacques Delors}}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/cta/events02/world/eur/euro/delors.ram Delors addressing the British trade unions]\n* The famous headline from ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' in the UK: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/nol/shared/spl/hi/pop_ups/06/programmes_enl_1146754853/img/1.jpg \"Up Yours Delors\"]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ren\u00e9 Monory]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of the Economy, Finances and Industry (France)|Minister of Finance]]|years=1981\u20131984}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pierre B\u00e9r\u00e9govoy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Ortoli]]<br />[[Edgard Pisani]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of European Commissioners by nationality#France|French European Commissioner]]|years=1985\u20131995|alongside=[[Claude Cheysson]], [[Christiane Scrivener]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[\u00c9dith Cresson]]<br />[[Yves-Thibault de Silguy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gaston Thorn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the European Commission]]|years=1985\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jacques Santer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Margaret Thatcher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Speaker at the [[College of Europe]] Opening Ceremony|years=1989}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{European Commission}}\n{{Finance Ministers of France}}\n{{Charlemagne Prize recipients}}\n{{UEFA President's Award}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for International Cooperation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delors, Jacques}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:French Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:French Confederation of Christian Workers members]]\n[[Category:French Democratic Confederation of Labour members]]\n[[Category:French economists]]\n[[Category:French European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:French Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]