{"title_page": "British 21-inch torpedo", "text_new": "{{short description|Class of torpedo in use during WWI to WWII}}\nThere have been several British 21-inch (533&nbsp;mm) diameter [[torpedo]]es used by the [[Royal Navy]] since their first development just before the First World War.\n\nThe 21-inch was the largest size of torpedo in common use in the RN. They were used by surface ships and submarines rather than aircraft which used smaller [[British 18-inch torpedo|18-inch torpedoes]].\n\n== Mark I ==\nThe first British 21-inch torpedo came in two lengths, \"Short\"  at 17&nbsp;ft 10.5 in (5.45 m), and \"Long\" at 23&nbsp;ft 1.25 in (7.04 m). The explosive charge was 200&nbsp;lb of [[gun cotton]] increased later to 225&nbsp;lb.\n\n== Mark II ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark II\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = heavy torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = c. 1914 \u2013 Second World War\n| used_by            = RN\n| wars               = First World War, Second World War\n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = c. 1910\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = \n| length             = \n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = TNT\n| filling_weight     = 400\u2013515 lb\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = wet heater\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 8,000 yards max depending on model\n| speed              = 29 to 35 knots\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nThe Mark II, chiefly used by destroyers, entered service in 1914. Apart from some older British ships, it was used with the old US ([[destroyers for bases]] agreement) [[Town-class destroyer]]s provided to the UK during the early part of the Second World War. The running speed was reduced from 45 knots (over 3,000 yards) for better reliability.\n\nThe Mark II*, an improved Mark II was used by battleships and battlecruisers. A [[wet heater]] design, it could run for {{convert|4.1|km|yd|abbr=on}} at {{convert|45|kn|km/h}}.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark IV ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark IV\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = c. 1916\u2013\n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = c. 1912\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = 3,206 lb (1,454&nbsp;kg)\n| length             = 22 ft 7.5 in (6.896 m)\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch (533&nbsp;mm)\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = TNT\n| filling_weight     = 515 lb (234&nbsp;kg)\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = Burner cycle\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 8,000 \u2013 13,500 yards\n| speed              = 25 \u2013 35 knots\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nFrom 1912, used by destroyers and other surface ships and was an important weapon in the first World War. In the Second World War they were carried on {{HMS|Hood|51|6}}.\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark V ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark V\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = \n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = 1917\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = \n| length             = {{convert|7.1|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = \n| filling_weight     = \n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = wet heater\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = {{convert|4.6|km|yd|abbr=on}} to {{convert|12.4|km|yd|abbr=on}}\n| speed              = {{convert|40|kn|km/h}} to {{convert|25|kn|km/h}}\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nThe Mark V was used by the [[A-class destroyer (1929)|A]] and [[B-class destroyer|B-class]] destroyers and, with modification, by the [[Kent-class cruiser|''Kent''-class]] heavy cruisers.\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark VII ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark VII\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = heavy torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = Second World War\n| used_by            = RN\n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = 1920s\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = \n| length             = 25 ft 6 in (7.77 m)\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = TNT\n| filling_weight     = 740 lb (336&nbsp;kg)\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = oxygen enriched air\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 5,700 yards (5,200&nbsp;m)\n| speed              = 35 knots\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nThe Mark VII was issued for use on the British heavy cruisers; i.e. cruisers with 8-inch guns. Designed in the mid-1920s the {{sclass2-|County|cruiser|2}}s were built at the same time in the post [[Washington Naval Treaty]] period.\n\nThe power came from the use of oxygen enriched air, though torpedo stocks were converted to run on normal air at the start of the Second World War.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark VIII ==\nSpecifications:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_WWII.htm|title=World War II Torpedoes of the United Kingdom/Britain \u2013 NavWeaps|first=Tony|last=DiGiulian|website=www.navweaps.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221135234/http://navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_WWII.htm|archivedate=21 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Sokol torpedo.jpg|250px|thumb|Mark VIIIs loading to [[Polish Navy]] submarine {{ORP|Sok\u00f3\u0142|1940|6}}]]\n'''Mark VIII'''\n* Entered Service: 1927\n* Weight: 3,452&nbsp;lb (1,566&nbsp;kg)\n\n* Length: {{convert|259|in|ft}} (6.58 m)\n* Explosive Charge: 750&nbsp;lb (340&nbsp;kg) [[Trinitrotoluene|TNT]]\n* Range & Speed: 5,000 yards (4,570&nbsp;m) / 40 knots\n\n'''Early Mark VIII**'''\n* Range & Speed: 5,000 yards (4,570&nbsp;m) / 45.6 knots\n* Explosive Charge: 722&nbsp;lb (327&nbsp;kg) [[Torpex]]\n\n'''Late Mark VIII**'''\n* Range & Speed: 7,000 yards (6,400&nbsp;m) / 41 knots\n* Explosive Charge: 805&nbsp;lb (365&nbsp;kg) Torpex\n\nThe Mark VIII was designed around 1925 and was the first British burner-cycle design torpedo. It was used from 1927 on submarines of the [[British O-class submarine|O class]] onwards and [[motor torpedo boat]]s. The principal World War II version was the improved Mark VIII**, 3,732 being fired by September 1944 (56.4% of the total number). The torpedo is still in service with the [[Royal Navy]] albeit in a limited role, and with the [[Royal Norwegian Navy]] (Coastal Artillery: Kaholmen torpedo battery at [[Oscarsborg Fortress]]) until 1993.\n\nThe Mark VIII** was used in two particularly notable incidents:\n\n* On [[Action of 9 February 1945|9 February 1945]] the Royal Navy submarine [[HMS Venturer (P68)|HMS ''Venturer'']] [[Action of 9 February 1945|sank the German submarine]] [[German submarine U-864|''U-864'']] with four Mark VIII** torpedoes. This is the only intentional wartime sinking of one submarine by another while both were submerged.\n\n* On 2 May 1982 the Royal Navy submarine {{HMS|Conqueror|S48|6}} sank the Argentine cruiser  {{ship|ARA|General Belgrano}} with three Mark VIII** torpedoes during the [[Falklands War]].<ref name=\"Belgrano sinking\">{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Colin |title=Sinking the Belgrano: the Pinochet connection |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/world-history/sinking-the-belgrano-the-pinochet-connection-7609047.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2012-05-02 |newspaper=The Independent |date=2012-04-03 |author2=Kim Sengupta |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67MXXmil5?url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/world-history/sinking-the-belgrano-the-pinochet-connection-7609047.html?origin=internalSearch |archivedate=2 May 2012 |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref> This is the only sinking of a surface ship by a nuclear-powered submarine in wartime (and only the second sinking of a surface ship by any submarine since the end of World War II).\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark IX ==\nFirst appeared in 1930 and was considerably improved by 1939. Used on\n[[Leander-class cruiser (1931)|''Leander'']] and later cruisers, \"A\" and later destroyer classes.\nAlso replaced the old Mark VII in some 8\" (20.3&nbsp;cm) cruisers during the war.\n\n== Mark X ==\nFrom 1939, used by submarines, motor torpedo boats and destroyers from other navies such as the [[Grom]]{{dn|date=July 2019}}.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n\n== Mark XI ==\nElectric battery powered torpedo with a {{convert|322|kg|lb|abbr=on}} TNT warhead. Entering service during the Second World War it was used by destroyers.\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark 12 ==\nAt first codenamed Ferry, then Fancy, the Mark 12 never reached production. From 1952, it had a warhead of {{convert|340|kg|lb|abbr=on}} Torpex.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\nUsing [[high test peroxide]] fuel, it attained a top speed of {{convert|28|kn|km/h}} for {{convert|5|km|yd|abbr=on}}.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\nThere were accidents during testing caused by the unstable nature of high test peroxide. One such engine explosion, after loading aboard the submarine [[HMS Sidon (P259)|HMS ''Sidon'']], caused enough damage to have the submarine taken permanently out of service.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\nMark 12 torpedoes were out of service in 1959 and the programme was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PostWWII.htm|title=Post-World War II Torpedoes of the United Kingdom/Britain \u2013 NavWeaps|first=Tony|last=DiGiulian|website=www.navweaps.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204081730/http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PostWWII.htm|archivedate=4 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n{{anchor|Mark20Bidder}}<!-- This Anchor tag serves to provide a permanent target for incoming section links. Please do not remove it, nor modify it, except to add another appropriate anchor.  If you modify the section title, please anchor the old title. It is always best to anchor an old section header that has been changed so that links to it will not be broken. See [[Template:Anchor]] for details. This template is {{subst:Anchor comment}} -->\n\n== Mark 20 Bidder ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark 20\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = 1955\u20131980s\n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = c. 1950\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = 1,810 lb (821&nbsp;kg)\n| length             = 6.46 m\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21 inches\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = \n| filling_weight     = 196 lb (89&nbsp;kg)\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = electric\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = battery\n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 12,000 yards (11,000&nbsp;m)\n| speed              = 20 knots\n| guidance           = passive sonar\n| steering           = \n}}\n\nDeveloped under the codename \"Bidder\", the Mark 20 was a passive-seeker battery-powered torpedo for use by surface ships (the Mark 20E \u2013 for \"Escort\") and submarines (Mark 20S). The E variant was not long in service due to problems with its programming. This led to several of the [[frigate]]s that were intended to have used them ([[Rothesay-class frigate|''Rothesay'']] and [[Whitby-class frigate|''Whitby'']] classes) never being fitted with torpedo tubes or having them removed.\n\nIt was replaced in the submarine service in the 1980s by [[Mark 24 Tigerfish|Tigerfish]].\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark 21 Pentane ==\nA project for an autonomous active/passive sonar torpedo to be carried by the [[Short Sturgeon]] anti-submarine aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skomer.u-net.com/projects/missiles.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601171206/http://www.skomer.u-net.com/projects/missiles.htm |archivedate=1 June 2009 }}</ref> It was cancelled after protracted work but the seeker development was used in Tigerfish.\n\n== Mark 22 ==\nA wire-guided version of the Mark 20 produced by [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering]] (VSEL) as a private venture.\n\n== Mark 23 Grog ==\nA wire-guided version of the Mark 20. Entered service in 1966 although already obsolescent, and did not become fully operational until 1971, serving only as an interim before Tigerfish entered service.\n\nThe MK23 was fitted with a 10,000 &nbsp;m outboard dispenser that contains a control wire to guide the weapon, During 1973, all of the RN torpedoes had to be taken out of service as the control system was failing at extreme range.\n\nAfter months of investigation, it was discovered that the fault lay in the Guidance Unit made by GEC. A germanium diode in the AGC circuit had been replaced by a silicon diode, following an instruction by RN stores that all germanium diodes had to be replaced by silicon diodes. Unfortunately, the silicon diode's different characteristics caused the automatic gain control circuit to fail. Once the mistake was found, replacing the diode with the original type cured the problem.\n\n== Mark 24 Tigerfish ==\n{{Main|Mark 24 Tigerfish}}\n\nThe first Tigerfish (Mod 0) entered service in 1980. Tigerfish was removed from service in 2004.\n\nThere were several models of Tigerfish due to the modifications made to tackle deficiencies.\n* Mark 24 Mod 0 Tigerfish\n* Mark 24 Mod 1 Tigerfish\n* Mark 24(N) Tigerfish\n* Mark 24 Mod 2 Tigerfish\n\n== Spearfish ==\n{{Main|Spearfish torpedo}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[British 18-inch torpedo]]\n* [[List of torpedoes]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite web |last=Tony DiGiulian |url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PreWWII.htm |title=British torpedoes Pre World War II}}\n* {{cite web |last=Tony DiGiulian |url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_WWII.htm |title=British Torpedoes of World War II}}\n* {{cite web |last=Tony DiGiulian |url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PostWWII.htm |title=British Torpedoes post World War II}}\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20100311033414/http://middle-watch.com/Torpedoes.htm\n\n{{Royal Navy torpedoes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Torpedoes of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Class of torpedo in use during WWI to WWII}}\nThere have been several British 21-inch (533&nbsp;mm) diameter [[torpedo]]es used by the [[Royal Navy]] since their first development just before the First World War.\n\nThe 21-inch was the largest size of torpedo in common use in the RN. They were used by surface ships and submarines rather than aircraft which used smaller [[British 18-inch torpedo|18-inch torpedoes]].\n\n== Mark I ==\nThe first British 21-inch torpedo came in two lengths, \"Short\"  at 17&nbsp;ft 10.5 in (5.45 m), and \"Long\" at 23&nbsp;ft 1.25 in (7.04 m). The explosive charge was 200&nbsp;lb of [[gun cotton]] increased later to 225&nbsp;lb.\n\n== Mark II ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark II\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = heavy torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = c. 1914 \u2013 Second World War\n| used_by            = RN\n| wars               = First World War, Second World War\n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = c. 1910\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = \n| length             = \n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = TNT\n| filling_weight     = 400\u2013515 lb\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = wet heater\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 8,000 yards max depending on model\n| speed              = 29 to 35 knots\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nThe Mark II, chiefly used by destroyers, entered service in 1914. Apart from some older British ships, it was used with the old US ([[destroyers for bases]] agreement) [[Town-class destroyer]]s provided to the UK during the early part of the Second World War. The running speed was reduced from 45 knots (over 3,000 yards) for better reliability.\n\nThe Mark II*, an improved Mark II was used by battleships and battlecruisers. A [[wet heater]] design, it could run for {{convert|4.1|km|yd|abbr=on}} at {{convert|45|kn|km/h}}.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark IV ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark IV\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = c. 1916\u2013\n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = c. 1912\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = 3,206 lb (1,454&nbsp;kg)\n| length             = 22 ft 7.5 in (6.896 m)\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch (533&nbsp;mm)\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = TNT\n| filling_weight     = 515 lb (234&nbsp;kg)\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = Burner cycle\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 8,000 \u2013 13,500 yards\n| speed              = 25 \u2013 35 knots\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nFrom 1912, used by destroyers and other surface ships and was an important weapon in the first World War. In the Second World War they were carried on {{HMS|Hood|51|6}}.\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark V ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark V\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = \n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = 1917\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = \n| length             = {{convert|7.1|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = \n| filling_weight     = \n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = wet heater\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = {{convert|4.6|km|yd|abbr=on}} to {{convert|12.4|km|yd|abbr=on}}\n| speed              = {{convert|40|kn|km/h}} to {{convert|25|kn|km/h}}\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nThe Mark V was used by the [[A-class destroyer (1929)|A]] and [[B-class destroyer|B-class]] destroyers and, with modification, by the [[Kent-class cruiser|''Kent''-class]] heavy cruisers.\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark VII ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark VII\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = heavy torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = Second World War\n| used_by            = RN\n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = 1920s\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = \n| length             = 25 ft 6 in (7.77 m)\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21-inch\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = TNT\n| filling_weight     = 740 lb (336&nbsp;kg)\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = oxygen enriched air\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 5,700 yards (5,200&nbsp;m)\n| speed              = 35 knots\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n}}\n\nThe Mark VII was issued for use on the British heavy cruisers; i.e. cruisers with 8-inch guns. Designed in the mid-1920s the {{sclass2-|County|cruiser|2}}s were built at the same time in the post [[Washington Naval Treaty]] period.\n\nThe power came from the use of oxygen enriched air, though torpedo stocks were converted to run on normal air at the start of the Second World War.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark VIII ==\nSpecifications:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_WWII.htm|title=World War II Torpedoes of the United Kingdom/Britain \u2013 NavWeaps|first=Tony|last=DiGiulian|website=www.navweaps.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221135234/http://navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_WWII.htm|archivedate=21 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Sokol torpedo.jpg|250px|thumb|Mark VIIIs loading to [[Polish Navy]] submarine {{ORP|Sok\u00f3\u0142|1940|6}}]]\n'''Mark VIII'''\n* Entered Service: 1927\n* Weight: 3,452&nbsp;lb (1,566&nbsp;kg)\n\n* Length: {{convert|259|in|ft}} (6.58 m)\n* Explosive Charge: 750&nbsp;lb (340&nbsp;kg) [[Trinitrotoluene|TNT]]\n* Range & Speed: 5,000 yards (4,570&nbsp;m) / 40 knots\n\n'''Early Mark VIII**'''\n* Range & Speed: 5,000 yards (4,570&nbsp;m) / 45.6 knots\n* Explosive Charge: 722&nbsp;lb (327&nbsp;kg) [[Torpex]]\n\n'''Late Mark VIII**'''\n* Range & Speed: 7,000 yards (6,400&nbsp;m) / 41 knots\n* Explosive Charge: 805&nbsp;lb (365&nbsp;kg) Torpex\n\nThe Mark VIII was designed around 1925 and was the first British burner-cycle design torpedo. It was used from 1927 on submarines of the [[British O-class submarine|O class]] onwards and [[motor torpedo boat]]s. The principal World War II version was the improved Mark VIII**, 3,732 being fired by September 1944 (56.4% of the total number). The torpedo is still in service with the [[Royal Navy]] albeit in a limited role, and with the [[Royal Norwegian Navy]] (Coastal Artillery: Kaholmen torpedo battery at [[Oscarsborg Fortress]]) until 1993.\n\nThe Mark VIII** was used in two particularly notable incidents:\n\n* On [[Action of 9 February 1945|9 February 1945]] the Royal Navy submarine [[HMS Venturer (P68)|HMS ''Venturer'']] [[Action of 9 February 1945|sank the German submarine]] [[German submarine U-864|''U-864'']] with four Mark VIII** torpedoes. This is the only intentional wartime sinking of one submarine by another while both were submerged.\n\n* On 2 May 1982 the Royal Navy submarine {{HMS|Conqueror|S48|6}} sank the Argentine cruiser  {{ship|ARA|General Belgrano}} with three Mark VIII** torpedoes during the [[Falklands War]].<ref name=\"Belgrano sinking\">{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Colin |title=Sinking the Belgrano: the Pinochet connection |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/world-history/sinking-the-belgrano-the-pinochet-connection-7609047.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2012-05-02 |newspaper=The Independent |date=2012-04-03 |author2=Kim Sengupta |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67MXXmil5?url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/world-history/sinking-the-belgrano-the-pinochet-connection-7609047.html?origin=internalSearch |archivedate=2 May 2012 |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref> This is the only sinking of a surface ship by a nuclear-powered submarine in wartime (and only the second sinking of a surface ship by any submarine since the end of World War II).\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark IX ==\nFirst appeared in 1930 and was considerably improved by 1939. Used on\n[[Leander-class cruiser (1931)|''Leander'']] and later cruisers, \"A\" and later destroyer classes.\nAlso replaced the old Mark VII in some 8\" (20.3&nbsp;cm) cruisers during the war.\n\n== Mark X ==\nFrom 1939, used by submarines, motor torpedo boats and destroyers from other navies such as the [[Grom]]{{dn|date=July 2019}}.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n\n== Mark XI ==\nElectric battery powered torpedo with a {{convert|322|kg|lb|abbr=on}} TNT warhead. Entering service during the Second World War it was used by destroyers.\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark 12 ==\nAt first codenamed Ferry, then Fancy, the Mark 12 never reached production. From 1952, it had a warhead of {{convert|340|kg|lb|abbr=on}} Torpex.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\nUsing [[high test peroxide]] fuel, it attained a top speed of {{convert|28|kn|km/h}} for {{convert|5|km|yd|abbr=on}}.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\nThere were accidents during testing caused by the unstable nature of high test peroxide. One such engine explosion, after loading aboard the submarine [[HMS Sidon (P259)|HMS ''Sidon'']], caused enough damage to have the submarine taken permanently out of service.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\nMark 12 torpedoes were out of service in 1959 and the programme was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PostWWII.htm|title=Post-World War II Torpedoes of the United Kingdom/Britain \u2013 NavWeaps|first=Tony|last=DiGiulian|website=www.navweaps.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204081730/http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PostWWII.htm|archivedate=4 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n{{anchor|Mark20Bidder}}<!-- This Anchor tag serves to provide a permanent target for incoming section links. Please do not remove it, nor modify it, except to add another appropriate anchor.  If you modify the section title, please anchor the old title. It is always best to anchor an old section header that has been changed so that links to it will not be broken. See [[Template:Anchor]] for details. This template is {{subst:Anchor comment}} -->\n\n== Mark 20 Bidder ==\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = 21-inch Mark 20\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| origin             = United Kingdom\n| type               = torpedo\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_explosive       = yes\n| is_missile         = yes\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = 1955\u20131980s\n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = c. 1950\n| manufacturer       = \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           = \n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = 1,810 lb (821&nbsp;kg)\n| length             = 6.46 m\n| part_length        = \n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = 21 inches\n| crew               = \n<!-- Explosive specifications -->\n| filling            = \n| filling_weight     = 196 lb (89&nbsp;kg)\n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| engine             = electric\n| engine_power       = \n| payload_capacity   = \n| propellant         = battery\n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = 12,000 yards (11,000&nbsp;m)\n| speed              = 20 knots\n| guidance           = passive sonar\n| steering           = \n}}\n\nDeveloped under the codename \"Bidder\", the Mark 20 was a passive-seeker battery-powered torpedo for use by surface ships (the Mark 20E \u2013 for \"Escort\") and submarines (Mark 20S). The E variant was not long in service due to problems with its programming. This led to several of the [[frigate]]s that were intended to have used them ([[Rothesay-class frigate|''Rothesay'']] and [[Whitby-class frigate|''Whitby'']] classes) never being fitted with torpedo tubes or having them removed.\n\nIt was replaced in the submarine service in the 1980s by [[Mark 24 Tigerfish|Tigerfish]].\n{{clear}}\n\n== Mark 21 Pentane ==\nA project for an autonomous active/passive sonar torpedo to be carried by the [[Short Sturgeon]] anti-submarine aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skomer.u-net.com/projects/missiles.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601171206/http://www.skomer.u-net.com/projects/missiles.htm |archivedate=1 June 2009 }}</ref> It was cancelled after protracted work but the seeker development was used in Tigerfish.\n\n== Mark 22 ==\nA wire-guided version of the Mark 20 produced by [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering]] (VSEL) as a private venture.\n\n== Mark 23 Grog ==\nA wire-guided version of the Mark 20. Entered service in 1971 although already obsolescent, serving only as an interim before Tigerfish entered service.\n\nThe MK23 was fitted with a 10,000 &nbsp;m outboard dispenser that contains a control wire to guide the weapon, During 1973, all of the RN torpedoes had to be taken out of service as the control system was failing at extreme range.\n\nAfter months of investigation, it was discovered that the fault lay in the Guidance Unit made by GEC. A germanium diode in the AGC circuit had been replaced by a silicon diode, following an instruction by RN stores that all germanium diodes had to be replaced by silicon diodes. Unfortunately, the silicon diode's different characteristics caused the automatic gain control circuit to fail. Once the mistake was found, replacing the diode with the original type cured the problem.\n\n== Mark 24 Tigerfish ==\n{{Main|Mark 24 Tigerfish}}\n\nThe first Tigerfish (Mod 0) entered service in 1980. Tigerfish was removed from service in 2004.\n\nThere were several models of Tigerfish due to the modifications made to tackle deficiencies.\n* Mark 24 Mod 0 Tigerfish\n* Mark 24 Mod 1 Tigerfish\n* Mark 24(N) Tigerfish\n* Mark 24 Mod 2 Tigerfish\n\n== Spearfish ==\n{{Main|Spearfish torpedo}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[British 18-inch torpedo]]\n* [[List of torpedoes]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite web |last=Tony DiGiulian |url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PreWWII.htm |title=British torpedoes Pre World War II}}\n* {{cite web |last=Tony DiGiulian |url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_WWII.htm |title=British Torpedoes of World War II}}\n* {{cite web |last=Tony DiGiulian |url=http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WTBR_PostWWII.htm |title=British Torpedoes post World War II}}\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20100311033414/http://middle-watch.com/Torpedoes.htm\n\n{{Royal Navy torpedoes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Torpedoes of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Axe99au", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMark 23 Grog:The source for this (Tony DiGuilan's article referenced on the page, which draws heavily on an article in Warship Volume V by Antony Preston) notes that the Mk 23 entered service in 1966, not 1971, but did not become fully operational until 1971.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_21-inch_torpedo"}
